etymologies: late Middle English: from Anglo-Latin baronettus, from Latin baro, baron- ‘man, warrior’. The term originally denoted a gentleman, not a nobleman, summoned by the king to attend parliament; the current order was instituted in the early 17th century

definitions: a member of the lowest hereditary titled British order, with the status of a commoner but able to use the prefix “Sir.”.
shortDefinitions: member of lowest hereditary titled British order, with status of commoner
